english:
  title: An Examination Question on the Way
  author: Lee Gye-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I ask: The great source of the Way flows from Heaven and is perfected within humanity. When put into practice, it becomes the governance of emperors and kings; when illuminated, it becomes the learning of sages and worthies. Yet governance and learning are not two different things.

    Looking back to antiquity: when Fuxi arose, the eight trigrams were drawn; when Yao and Shun flourished, the five canons were established. Yu, Tang, Wen, and Wu became sovereigns; Hou Ji, Xie, Yi Yin, and Fu Yue became ministers—all inherited the transmission of the Way and thus achieved the splendor of perfect harmony. Can we not desire to hear the details of this?

    When Zhou declined, no sage-kings arose. Confucius, though Heaven-gifted with sagehood, could not practice the Way in his own age. Yet through his editing and commentary, the teachings of the Six Classics shone like the sun at zenith. Yan Hui, Zengzi, Zisi, and Mencius all received and transmitted this legacy. But after Mencius passed away, our Way grew dim—consumed by Qin's flames, distorted by Han scholars' literalism. From then onward, all became confused and turbulent. Some mixed kingly and hegemonic ways; others fell into the traps of Daoism and Buddhism. That the Way remained obscure and unexecuted is hardly surprising.

    Then in the Song, scholars of Lian, Luo, Guan, and Min appeared in succession, illuminating the principles of righteousness, and the Way of the Six Classics shone forth anew. Yet it suffered repeated calamities and never found full expression in practice. Why does Heaven's plan not support this?

    Honored is the great Taizong, the Cultured Emperor, who commanded Confucian ministers to compile the Four Books, Five Classics, and the Great Compendium of Nature and Principle, which were promulgated to our Eastern land. Was this not to enable us to clarify the Great Way and illuminate the Ultimate Governance?

    Respectfully considering our Lord and Sovereign: through refined and unified learning, you perfect the Way of sage-ruler and teacher. As ministers, we think to aid the governance of the Six Classics; as scholars, we also study their learning. Today, does all governance align with the Six Classics? What does not yet accord with them? To fully realize the Way and governance of the Six Classics, what should come first and what should come after? You scholars, familiar with the profound mysteries of Nature and Principle, versed in the gains and losses of statecraft—answer not with empty words or careless thoughts, but with your whole heart and mind.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Four Books (四書) include the Analects, Mencius, Great Learning, and Doctrine of the Mean; the Five Classics (五經) are the Book of Changes, Book of History, Book of Poetry, Book of Rites, and Spring and Autumn Annals.
  - key: ''
    value: 'Lian, Luo, Guan, and Min (濂洛關閩) refer to the Northern Song Neo-Confucian schools: Zhou Dunyi''s Liandu tradition, the Cheng brothers'' Luoyang school, Zhang Zai''s Guanzhong philosophy, and Zhu Xi''s Min tradition.'
  - key: ''
    value: This is an examination question (策題), a form of imperial civil service examination testing candidates' understanding of classical learning and governance.
